text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!SignLanguage]]%0a%0a!"Manual" Non-Manual Markers in Pro-Tactile ASL%0a%0a:Author: CharlieP%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aPro-Tactile ASL makes use of many manual forms of non-manual markers to convey inferred information about a conversation. %0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aSomething that I've found interesting is how in Pro-Tactile ASL, a version of ASL largely used with touch and speakers who are both deaf and blind, there are parts that formally denote things that would be naturally inferred from non-manual markers visually.Typically, for sighted ASL users, this involves nodding, vocal cues, body language, and facial expression. However, for users of PASL, terms that make sense in ASL don't make sense without the corresponding visual cues. %0a%0aFor PASL, this same information is encoded manually, in six specific categories: Prolonged Hold, Specific or Extra Sign, Tenseness of the Hand, Extended Location, Longer and Slower Movement, and Redundancy. These categories are each used to mark degree/manner, time, duration, frequency, purpose, and place/position/direction. For example, to illustrate speed or a small amount of time, the signing is sped up and possibly tension is increased in the signer's hand or wrist. %0a%0aAdditionally, in visual ASL, movements of the head indicate negation and question formation, but these cannot be observed by a deafblind person. In PASL, signs such as "NOT" and "NO" are used to indicate negation. Furthermore, PASL has signs for feelings and moods, such as "WOW", "IMPRESSED", "PUZZLED", and "QUESTION." These are all visually indicated in ASL through facial expressions and head movements, and these manual signs work to replace them. %0a%0aSource: %0ahttp://www.deafblind.com/card.html%0ahttps://digitalcommons.wou.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1133&context=honors_theses%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a(:section: D:)%0a(:Category: SignLanguage:)
